metadata.name: Floating Medusas #99
metadata.description:
Floating Medusas is a generative piece. A group of little creatures creating an organic visual. 

The size, position and frequency of creatures are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  Each creature is masking by a geometric pattern. Creatures have straight or smooth edges.
The shapes’s sizes of the patterns are visible as features, like the edge’s type and the number of creatures.  

Handmade by code with javascript, made with fragment.tools 
Quentin Hocdé, Brussels (Belgium), 2022

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Root #17
metadata.description:
Root, by Matthew Plummer-Fernandez (2022). A pseudo-simulation of plant intelligence and root systems. Each root apex splinters into more apexes that follow similar trajectories in swarm-like patterns. To illustrate a basic response to their surroundings, each root system is confined to an invisible container that the root tips appear to either inspect or repel from, framing the final state. The system is sensitive to the space containing it, so it may grow in another way on different screen sizes. 

Inspired by The Revolutionary Genius of Plants: A New Understanding of Plant Intelligence and Behavior, by scientist and author Stefano Mancuso.

Press 's' key in live mode to save a png.

The code that generates this work also contains an essay titled 'Root: hashing out the concept of regenerative art'

Press the '/' key (a symbol used for the 'root' directory) in live mode to save the essay as a txt file (best viewed copy/pasted into a word processor).

metadata.name: CHX-1 #170
metadata.description:
Glitching pixels like it’s 1999.

Inspired by 90’s digital aesthetics, CHX-1 takes a random selection of GAN seeds, combines them in unique ways, and processes them –individually and as a group– with a series of glitching dithering algorithms. Generating fun, original, colorful artworks. Millions of possibilities. Have fun!

<<< Base seeds generated offline using personal styleGAN2-ADA models. Image processing and combinations done generatively by the CHX-1 algorithm >>>

GAN –> p5js –> Blockchain


• Artworks can take a few seconds to load when running live code.

• Press “s” (when "open live" is active) to save a PNG image.

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #388
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: A Poem #3
metadata.description:
An abstract representation of a poem written with signs and ink drops. Inspiring heart and emotion, escaping the logic and rationale mind. Providing hints and indication of joy and love. 

This work, like all others, builds upon my constant research of recreating in the generative world the artistic gesture explored in the physical one: painting with a palette knife, with large brushes or dripping colours on the canvas.

- hit 'p' for .png export

metadata.name: Connections - v2 #53
metadata.description:
Dear collectors,
Roots was originally published as Project #1374 on November 26, 2021.
(https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/1374)
Due to a technical issue, Project #1374 has been hidden from the site and is being replaced by this reissued version.

_______________________________
Lets connect?

Connections (v1) showed in the description of its previous version an outburst of Brazilian citizens dissatisfied with their loss of monetary power due to the corruption of their government.

Now, in more mature way, this project draws luminous connections made thanks to the encounter of colored particles of a flowfield inside a Voronoi diagram, whose transparency is mapped according to the animation, bringing smoothness and fading in the transitions. As a result, we have different population divisions of these particles, like civilizations entering conurbatory processes, photographed on a dark night.

Possible Features:
> Background: Night, Blood, Deep Ocean, Wine, Swamp and Steel.
> Line colors: Reggae, Cold, Neon and Nature.
> Connection Factor: 1, 3, 7 and 11.
> Particles: 222, 333, 888, 1111 and 2222.


Go to Live View window ("open live") and press 's' to save a PNG from your canvas.

_______________________________

Nov2021 -> Nov2022
